<br>
I've recieved the counter argument that if I'm *invited* along and do as much work as anyone else, then I should get the chance to roll on items.. as they feel I've earned it.<br>
<br>
And I agree with that attitude, but the main reason I refrained was because I knew that chaos and bitchiness would errupt if I dared think of myself, someone invited along, as equal to everyone else.<br>
<br>
I *signed up* for two raids.. One, Fear, when I was still a member of CDF. The second was Dragon Necropolis, which I removed myself from. The rest I was *invited* along to. <br>
<br>
So, instead of having a flying hissy fit saying &quot;Non Fed's shouldn't get stuff!&quot; you should think about the situation a bit more. Those non-Fed members.. Did they get invited on the raid? Did they contribute their efforts, their items/money, and their time? Did they help the raid? Did they support the raid? Did they teleport 15 people to the raid? <br>
<br>
What I'm saying here us thus - if you invite someone along because the raid is lacking something, don't make them a second class citizen. It makes the raid leader and his/her assistants, as well as the Federation, look pretty bad.<br>
<br>
Raid Leaders get the final say on who is or is not welcome. If someone from outside of the Federation is asked to join in, they should have the same rights as anyone else on that raid. (Which includes the right to say 'Nono, nothing for me, just happy to help.')<br>
<br>
If the Raid leader doesn't want any non-Federation members along, under any circumstances, then you don't have to worry about non-Fed's &quot;getting stuff.&quot;<br>
<br>
There. Problem solved. <p><HR><BR>
